I would love to see the Berkeley protocols documented - in my opinion
this is the one major flaw in some otherwise very useful protocols.
If anyone at Berkeley is listening, please write up some RFC's on
lpd, rlogin, rsh, ruptime, syslog, and whatever else you've invented.

One comment on a "byte-per-protocol" representation - you don't have
to go to two bytes but you can still handle ports &gt; 255 if you use
the tricks that OSI uses for length codes.  Up to 127 means the port
number, but if the high bit is set, the low 7 bits are the length
of the data to follow.

	Mark

